@S @v(have|has) an unbalanced opening hand with no five-card major, so @v(open|opens) the longest suit. 1\D shows 5+ diamonds and 12+ points and leaves the most room to describe the hand on the next round.
[BID 2H]
This jump to 2\H is the Soloway jump shift: a game force with slam interest, about 17+ points, four or more controls, and a good suit. @S @v(promise|promises) a strong hand and a real heart suit, telling partner to start investigating slam.
[BID 3H]
Raising responder's suit shows three-card support and a willingness to cooperate toward slam. @S @v(set|sets) hearts as trumps so the partnership can stop guessing strain and turn to counting keycards.
[BID 4N]
With trumps agreed and slam in the air, 4NT is Roman Keycard Blackwood. @S @v(ask|asks) for the number of keycards — the four aces plus the trump king — so the partnership can judge whether all the controls are present.
[BID 5C]
This step answers the keycard ask, showing the agreed number of aces-plus-trump-king. @S @v(give|gives) the precise count so partner can add it to @your own holding and place the contract.
[BID 5D]
This continuation is a follow-up ask in the keycard structure, checking for the trump queen or a further control. @S @v(keep|keeps) the slam investigation going rather than guessing.
[BID 5S]
The answer here confirms the missing card the partnership needed to hear about. @S @v(round|rounds) out the picture so partner can count twelve tricks with confidence.
[BID 6H]
With all the keycards accounted for, @S @v(bid|bids) the small slam in the agreed trump suit. The Soloway sequence has done its work: a strong responding hand and a fitting opener combine for a sound 6\H.
[show NS] North's jump shift showed a strong hand with a good suit and real slam interest, and South's 1\D opener with the heart fit and useful aces filled the gaps. The keycard exchange confirmed the partnership held everything needed, landing a comfortable heart slam.}
